I'm interested in what a state and/or locality might theoretically do
if there's a law at a higher level that they disagree with.

For example, assume that the San Francisco decides that the current
drug laws are a crock.  Some of those laws are purely federal and
enforced by the DEA, but some are state and normally enforced by
the SFPD.  So the city council passes an ordinance that says that
those sections of the California Penal Code are the absolute lowest
priority for the Police and other public safety agencies in the city.
*Any* other activity has higher priority -- as long as there's any
unanswered call anywhere in the city, any work they can do, they are
to do that first -- even leave a drug arrest in progress to answer a
parking enforcement call.

And since the City and County of San Francisco are the same entity,
they could also order the DA to give lowest priority to drug cases.
In practice I think that would mean they would have to be nolle
prosse'd, or perhaps allowed to be dismissed for failure to provide a
trial in the legally required time frame.

What could the state do?  Can they order an incorporated city to
change its priorities.  I suppose the CHP can go in and do drug
enforcement, but I doubt they have very many CHiPs to spare from their
usual duties (policing the state's freeways).  And the state Attorney
General could, in theory, remove cases from the county's DA and handle
them in his office.

What else can the state do?  What else can the city do to vitiate a
law they don't like?

And what can a state do about a US law they don't like?  Out-and-out
nullification isn't allowed -- that was settled in the 18th century.
But they can (I think) refuse to cooperate with the DEA/FBI on those
cases.  Can they go further?  Could San Francisco have its police
monitor DEA radio frequencies and show up at drug busts in the city?
They wouldn't be allowed to interfere with the DEA agents, but I would
think they could order their police to show up, record and photograph
are preserved, no?

Any other ideas?  What else could a state or city do?  What could the
higher-level government entity do in response, either to force the
lower-level government to enforce the law, or to dissuade it from its
current course of action?

For discussion purposes, assume that the federal and state constitutions
are followed, rather than that some sort of super-executive privilege or
&quot;it's an emergency&quot; override of normal procedure (like the so-called
USA PATRIOT acts).
