Barry,

You ask what local government can do about laws it does not want to
enforce? The answer is that they do not enforce those laws. Around here
almost naked ladies strut around in establishments that serve alcohol. There
are a number of laws that may be used to harass the ladies and the
establishments. The local DA (elected at the county level) made it clear
(quite publicly, this was some years ago) that he would not prosecute such
cases. He was re-elected several times. Eventually attitudes changed, he
moved on, and a DA was elected who closed down a bunch of the bars.
Note that the law did not change, only the enforcement. This is quite
common.
The DA is locally elected but he technically works for the State-wide
elected AG. The AG can over-ride the DA by appointing a special prosecutor
to deal with naked ladies. Then such cases will be prosecuted, but only if
the local police decide to start arresting the naked ladies. The local
police work very closely with the local DA and do not want to piss him off.
I imagine it's the same everywhere. Note that this system encourages
corruption.
You ask whether a local police force can interfere with another police
force's prosecution of cases. Once again I'm left wondering if you read the
newspapers. The answer is yes, and it does happen. People have been informed
that the business needs to be really, really clean on Wed. because that's
when the door will be kicked in.

Good luck,
