In Massachusetts District Attorney is an elected position.
The county government, in those few counties which still
have government, has no direct authority to set policy.

We have prosecutorial nullification already, not as much for
controversial laws like drug possession as for unpopular laws
with tenure.  You don't see much prosecution for adultery.
Rape charges are rarely brought when he's 16 and she's 15.
Police do it too: bicyclists are rarely charged with traffic
law violations and pedestrians almost never are.  Enforcing
speed limit laws as written is highly unpopular and rarely
done in the United States.  I don't mean writing a lot of
tickets or writing for small amounts over the limit.  I mean
really enforcing the letter of the law.  In Victoria, Australia
there are cameras that ticket substantially every vehicle that
passes at 3 km/h (2 mph) or more over the limit.

