On Fri, 07 Sep 2007 07:28:39 -0400, bg ... @nyx3.nyx.net (Barry Gold) wrote:
&gt;What else can the state do?  What else can the city do to vitiate a
&gt;law they don't like?
">

Except where certain state constitutions allow otherwise, city governments
are merely creations of the state government, which grants these governments
their charter.  They are subject to the control of the unitary authority of the
state government, which can, in theory, do anything up to and including
revoking their charter and directly exercising authority over the city.

They are more likely to exercise less drastic measures, however, such as
suing the mayor or police chief asking the court for a writ of mandamus
ordering them, essentially, to do their job.  I can't think of a case offhand
of a city government being dissolved involuntarily, perhaps because doing
so would be extremely unpopular.

In actuality, the power of a city government to be obstructionist, drag
their feet, do a poor job of enforcing a law even if ordered to enforce it
by a court, or otherwise weaken policies they don't like is likely to exist
to some extent, unless and until it becomes something about which the
state government feels compelled to expend a lot of effort bringing
the city government to heel.

But in theory, the city government IS simply a smaller unit of the state
government, cf. Dillon's Rule, Hunter v. Pittsburgh, 207 U.S. 161 (1907),
etc.
