You should read the other articles on this thread.  Perhaps the term I
should have used is &quot;vitiate&quot;: to render ineffective.  If the
higher-level government is dependent on a lower level to enforce the
law, there is little they can do if the lower level chooses to expend
its limited resources on other matters.

Perhaps one good example would be the &quot;double-nickel&quot; -- the law
requiring a maximum speed limit of 55 everywhere throughout the
states.  Of course, the Federal government does not have direct
jurisdiction over state highways (including the &quot;Interstate Highway
System&quot;, built by the states with mostly Federal money).  So Congress
put in a clause that states had to enact that limit or lose their
share of Federal highway construction money.

So the state legislatures duly enacted a 55 MPH maximum speed limit.
And motorists ignored it, and state and local police had other things
to worry about.  So Congress then required states to measure the
speeds on highways and keep a certain percentage of traffic below a
stated value.  That resulted in some enforcement, but speeds on rural
interstates still averaged well over 65(*) (by my observation on the
I-5 through California's Central Valley).  Eventually the public grew
so weary of this charade that the state of Montana told Congress where
they could put their highway money, and the double-nickel was repealed
a few years later.

(*) Excluding multi-part vehicles like tractor-trailer rigs.
