By posting 70 miles per hour on an Interstate Nevada staged a revolt
that lasted the two hours it took for the federal government to inform
the state that no more money would be forthcoming.  Armed with a live
controversy, Nevada went to court and lost.

Montana's resistance was a $5 ticket for waste of resources for
those driving at a safe speed over 55.  Several other states had
speeding tickets with no &quot;points&quot; for speeds between 55 and the
former speed limit.  Some are still on the books.  Michigan's law
was invalidated a year or two ago due to a procedural error in
its passage many years earlier.

By the early 1990s the level of dishonesty in the certifications
of compliance with the national speed limit was rising and eventually
the Federal Highway Administration would have been forced to stop
looking the other way and start taking away money.  As of 1995
states were officially permitted to lie by up to five miles per
hour -- thus explaining the reported rise of speeds after speed
limits went up and there was no motive to lie -- and were unofficially
permitted to measure speed right after a visible speed trap.

What finally killed the national speed limit was a combination
of the Republican takeover of Congress, lobbying by the National
Motorists Association, and the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration's failed attempt to suppress a report it sponsored
that, contrary to the agency's intent, found that the numbers on
speed limit signs didn't really do anything.  The people would
have gone on agreeing that dangerous speeds over 65 must never
be tolerated as long as they were each individually permitted to
keep driving 70-75.

Although the national speed limit was repealed, the attitude it
created remains.  In most places the numbers on speed limit signs
have no relation to the safe speed or the speed which will result
in a speeding ticket.  The signs are merely decorative.

